library(mosaic)

soecol <- read_csv("soecol.csv")

Intro/Context

The data set used for this analysis contains sales information (# of units sold) by week and by month of the company SOECOL. They have been struggling with the number of employees that they hire every season because they don’t know for sure what should be the average # of employees that they should hire every month in order to make sure that they can produce enough products to satisfy the sales orders. This analysis is to see which months will require higher # of employees. The hypotheses for this analysis are shown below

Ho/Ha (ANOVA)

The null hypotheses assumes that the average number of units sold every month is equal and don’t different from each other. We will take a closer ook at the result to analyze what are the month when the company needs to hire more employees.

\[ H_0: \mu \text {Jan} = \mu \text{Feb} = \mu \text{Mar} = \mu \text{Apr} = \mu \text{May} = \mu \text{Jun} = \mu \text{Jul} = \mu \text{Aug} = \mu \text{Sep} = \mu \text{Oct} = \mu \text{Nov} = \mu \text{Dec} = \mu \]

\[ H_a: \mu_i \neq \mu \]

\[ α=0.05 \]

Graphical Summary

This graph shows the data of units sold grouped by month. We can see a peak that in month 9/September it seems that they sell more units, however, we will proceed to perform an ANOVA test to determine more precisely if we reject or fail to reject the null hypotheses to be able to come up with a conclusion.

xyplot(Units ~ Month, data=soecol, main="Units Sold by Month", ylab="Units Sold", xlab="Month", type=c("p","a"))

Numerical Summary

In this numerical summary we can see the in month 9, 10, and 11 they sell the most during a given year. September seems to be the month with the highest sales of the year and oactober seems to have the highest median of units sold.

ANOVA Test

soecol.aov <- aov(Units ~ as.factor(Month), data = soecol) 
  pander(summary(soecol.aov))
Analysis of Variance Model
  Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
as.factor(Month) 11 6801775 618343 3.832 0.001071
Residuals 36 5808837 161357 NA NA

The P-value for this is test is 0.04648 which is lower than the significance level used for this test of α = 0.05.

Check the Requirements

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(soecol.aov, which= 1:2)

These two graph show the Residual vs Fitted on the left and the Normal Q-Q plot on the right. We can see that there are some outliers as shown in both graphs, and it’s because of these inconsistencies that a non-parametric test like Kruskal-Wallis would be more appropriate for this analysis. (The ouliers are in values 34, 35, and 36)

Kruskal-Wallis Rank Sum Test

Since the requirements have not been met for an ANOVA test, we are moving forward and conducting a Kruskal-Wallis Rank Sum Test as follows

pander(kruskal.test(Units ~ as.factor(Month), data = soecol))
Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test: Units by as.factor(Month)
Test statistic df P value
23.58 11 0.01462 *

Based on the results after performing a Kruskal-Wallis type of test, we see that the p-value for this tests is p-value = 0.01462, which is lower than the significance level of 0.05. Based on this p-value results we can say that under the Kruskal-Walling conditions, we still reject the null hypotheses and accept the alternative which is the same results and conclusion of the ANOVA. However, the p-values for the ANOVA and Kruskal-Wallis are different.

Conclusion/Future Studies

The ANOVA test had a p-value = 0.04648 < α = 0.05. We conclude that we reject the null hypotheses, accepting that overall the 12 different groups/months have significantly difference on average of Unit sold. The three month with the highest sales are September, October, and November (In that order), Soecol should plant for hiring more people since August in preparation fro the productions of units for the next three month with the highest sales.

soecol |> 
    group_by(Month) |> 
   summarise(Units_Average = mean(Units)) |>
